tps%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F69988028efb52c8bd0de8c86%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22683%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20fuselage%20of%20the%20Enola%20Gay%20on%20display%20at%20the%20National%20Air%20and%20Space%20Museum%20in%20Washington%2C%20DC%2C%20in%201995.%3Cp%3EJeffrey%20Markowitz%2FSygma%20via%20Getty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIn%201995%2C%20the%20fuselage%20and%20other%20parts%20of%20the%20Enola%20Gay%20were%20displayed%20at%20the%20National%20Air%20and%20Space%20Museum's%20flagship%20location%20in%20Washington%2C%20DC%2C%20in%20an%20exhibit%20tied%20to%20the%2050th%20anniversary%20of%20the%20bombing%20of%20Hiroshima.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20script%20of%20the%20exhibit%20was%20rewritten%20several%20times%20as%20various%20interest%20groups%20debated%20how%20it%20was%20presented%20and%20how%20the%20decision%20to%20drop%20the%20bomb%20was%20framed%2C%20according%20to%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsiarchives.si.edu%2Fblog%2Fexhibiting-enola-gay%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESmithsonian%20Institution%20Archives%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EVeterans'%20groups%20pushed%20for%20the%20exhibit%20to%20emphasize%20Japanese%20aggression%20and%20present%20the%20narrative%20that%20dropping%20the%20atomic%20bomb%20saved%20lives%20by%20ending%20the%20war.%20Anti-war%20activists%20opposed%20having%20the%20exhibit%20justify%20the%20use%20of%20the%20bomb%20and%20sought%20to%20highlight%20its%20victims%20by%20protesting%20with%20alternative%20exhibits%20on%20the%20sidewalk%20outside%20the%20museum.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3EThe%20Enola%20Gay%20went%20on%20permanent%20display%20at%20the%20National%20Air%20and%20Space%20Museum's%20Steven%20F.%20Udvar-Hazy%20Center%20in%202003.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221024%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20Enola%20Gay%20Superfortress%20bomber%20at%20the%20Smithsonian%20Air%20and%20Space%20Museum's%20Udvar-Hazy%20Center%20ahead%20of%20its%20opening%20in%202003.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%